\
	The most commonly used HTTP method is the GET method for retrieving resources. If the resource is public, the GET method only needs the method and the URL in order to work. If the resource sits behind a security wall, the request may need an authorisation header which contains an encrypted username and password, and maybe a cookie containing an authorisation token. If the get request is successful, a status response code of 200 is returned in the response, along with the requested data. If the request is unsuccessful, the response may contain a 403 code (user does not have sufficient permissions for the resource), a 404 code (resource not found), or a 405 code (resource blocked by the server).\
